Bakal's tenant: The poles are warming, he has signed a higher rent.
An elderly man came out the door of the RPG Byty customer center of the "coal baron" Zdenek Bakal, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
He was carrying a file with three new leases for three apartments: his own, that of his daughter and that of his son who is serving a sentence.
The deregulation increased the rent to these three people.
Instead of paying 3,500 the son will have to pay from next year for a 2+1 apartment of second category 4100 crowns.
“And there’s no hot water and the heating runs on solid fuel,” points to the new contract of his son the man who has the power to sign.
"But I signed anyway," he said, angry and half resigned.
The citizen association of BytyOKD.cz apartments that described the new rental conditions as “immoral and indecent”, advises renters not to sign and wait until December 7, when a notice will be published to explain the method to follow to claim.
But the man reacts to this with a hand gesture.
“One says this, the other says something else” by frowning.
The Ostrava region becomes the laboratory of deregulation.
After the New Year, this is what most apartments in the Czech Republic expect, whose rents do not match the market price.
Aktualne.cz has therefore decided to personally visit the "laboratory".
The RPG waiting room in Havirovska Street is one of four in the Ostrava region and is already full on Tuesdays at 9 a.m.
Right next to the door stands a security company guard with a device to call customers.
A special button, "rent 2011", is lit on the touch screen.
A single press and a paper with a number comes out of the device.
You don’t have time to read your “157” number as your number is already starting to light up on the big screen under the top of the waiting room.
In a fraction of a second, it's your turn.
After a short while, an old couple arrives to find out about the rent, but the new rents do not seem to concern the people in the waiting room.
The majority of people have come to solve common problems as everywhere - claims for repairs, events concerning insurance and others.
In the Ostrava region, people from more than 44,000 apartments in the RPG portfolio have been receiving mail with new leases in their mailboxes since about mid-November.
RPG Byty offers rent increases from 15 percent to 38 percent.
The special window for new rents has been open to the public since November 18.
"It's been working for almost a week, so it's still on trial," says the employee, after a moment of hesitation, behind the counter when the client shows up as a journalist.
Bakal deregulation and old miner apartments are a very sensitive local topic.
The vice-president of parliament and from the Ostrava Lubomir Zaoralek region of the Social Democrats reported this fairly strongly before the elections and it now fills the local newspapers.
“Twenty years after them, I want a new floor.”
"They didn't even change a put...n of board in the toilets," said the man mentioned in the introduction.
However, these are mostly, according to employees, retirees who come to make sure they will receive a discount on the new rent price if they sign now as promised by RPG in a special offer.
This is a discount of half the amount of rent that will be received by the other tenants who will have signed their new contract before December 15.
But the "deregulation" window on Havirovaska Street is really not overwhelmed by questions.
“Among the 360 customers who came yesterday, only 40 to 50 came for rent,” the employee said at the counter.
And yet RPG puts individual rent interviews on its website as well as in the windows when it is needed.
If the two sides do not agree on the rent, an independent court will make the decision.
“It’s not about threats, it’s just about informing you about the unique and legitimate way to act legally,” RPG said on its website.
“No one will go to court here,” thinks one of Byty’s RPG employees and the man in the street in front of the customer center is right.
“I have 13,000 retirement crowns and I have 5000 crowns left to eat, I don’t have enough to go to court,” he says.
The employee suddenly feels uncomfortable.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaoralek in the media asks that no one sign and therefore people wait," she said.
Rent regulation ends in the Czech Republic in early 2011 and increases, according to RPG Byty, are an economic necessity.
"And, moreover, current rents are still not reaching the level necessary for the simple maintenance of the housing fund," recalls Pavel Klimes, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, that it is precisely the neglect of the housing fund that makes the tenant angry is the main reason for the rent increase.
However in 5 years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest with rents in 4 billion apartments, in four years from 2011 to 2014 this is expected to make 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling in front of the upholstered armchairs of the waiting room on Havirosvka Street, however, repeats some information indicated in red.
“The rent increase in 2011 is 15 percent and concerns no less than 31,200 apartments or more than 90 percent of RPG apartments.”
"And it will always be at most 7.50 Czech kronor per m2 per month," the screen says.
The 38 percent increase concerns only 400 apartments in the RPG portfolio.
“In these cases, it is an increase of a really very low sum of 19.66 Czech kronor per m2,” adds RPG.
Next year the rent will remain the same for 2,600 apartments.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not cause a radical but gradual increase over 4 to 8 years.
It adds other commitments: all the money from the rent increase (see graph) is returned to the apartments in the form of heating savings - new windows and heating.
Those who sign the rent increase agreement have priority.
The kindergarten is also part of the offices understood by the architects.
Brno’s Avriopoint administrative building is the new headquarters of Arch. Design.
No one could have expected it to also house a mini kindergarten with everything you need - colorful walls, imaginative furniture, toys and finally a miniature playground on the terrace.
Since October of last year, the children of Arch. design employees can go there.
The architectural project company Arch. Design. whose workshops have produced a large number of buildings in Brno, has imagined its mini business kindergarten since the first drafts of the Avriopoint building.
It employs about 90 people, mostly of childbearing age, and it was important to her that women architects and project managers could quickly return to work.
At the same time as reduced time contracts, kindergarten is a bonus offered to its employees by the company Arch. Design. as part of its social program.
Builders and architects have the opportunity to combine work with care for children.
The employees of Arch.Design.themselves imagined this kindergarten and with the support of the management they were able to obtain an endowment from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The mini kindergarten is financed through the European Social Fund through the Czech Republic’s Human Resources Operational Programme and State Budget.
They were able to purchase equipment and appliances and after two years to provide qualified staff and start-up.
After the use of the funding (two years) the company Arch. Design. is obliged after 3 years to operate the mini kindergarten on its own funds.
The preparation of the project lasted a year and it was the company Economy rating that helped to apply for staffing.
The care of the children is provided by qualified staff, all day a nurse and kindergarten teacher take care of the children. children can go to kindergarten without age limitation but they are over threeyearsfor most.
As this is a "mini kindergarten" there can only be 5 children present at the same time, but during the day there are more that are replaced.
The operation of the school is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use this school without regard to the hierarchical position.
Although it involves individual care and education, the curriculum of the mini kindergarten is comparable to that for preschool education.
Children do not only play there but quality teaching is also ensured - from the beginning to the preparation at the school benches English is taught.
The class is equipped not only with imaginative toys and games but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children in society creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can at any time control their child and not have the stress of a delay to pick up the children from a school far from the parents’ workplace.
Parents use their work time in the most productive way.
It is no wonder that a natural relationship of loyalty is created between the employee and the employer.
Arch.Design.s is among the companies that offer a bonus of choice for the recruitment of new employees and are friendly to the family and through this program strengthens HR marketing.
The bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Take a look at Gaudi's interiors.
The toss looks like the back of a prehistoric saurian, the staircase to a dinosaur spine and the balconies to open fish mouths.
This is how the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona by the architect Antoni Gaudi is.
Due to its organic shapes, the house has received from the locals the nickname House in Bone.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaic, facade reminiscent of scales and everywhere present curves, this is all that is epic for Antoni Gaudi’s Art Nouveau.
The front facade of the house unfolds its dream lines, its pleasant colors and textures that remind nature and animals.
In the course of a more detailed observation we see geometry, rhythm and order thought with precision.
At night the facade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of brilliance of the colors is reinforced.
The winding and twisting of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measurement.
Wood copies in waves the window frames, balustrades, decorative elements of the doors, the eyelet and the slats.
The Battlo house that stands in the Eixample district in the shopping street Passeig de Gracia at number 43, was born from the construction of a house of 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
Reconstruction was carried out for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy entrepreneur, initially insisted on the demolition of the old building and the construction of a brand new one but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-housing house was not thought of by Gaudi alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It was precisely on his project that the decorations for a representative apartment of the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the facade were born.
For the facade have also worked other artists and creators.
The joint work for Casa Battlo began with successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of the house of Gaudi Casa Mila and Guell Park in which there are other works of Gaudi.
The locals nicknamed the house hot right after it was finished because of its organic forms "the House in bone".
Others, with regard to the specific mechanism of opening the windows have called it "the house that swings".
It is said that at the top of the building there is a sword similar to that of Saint George, the patron saint of Catalonia.
Other sculpture elements of the building contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi thought for the house a unique system in its central heating time, with typical vents and fireplaces.
Their 45-degree tilt seems strange.
During the creation Gaudi absolutely did not respect the construction guidelines of the time and did not allow himself to be hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained from the city the permit to build, knowing, of course, that the data carried on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the completion the city council was horrified and asked for changes.
For example, the members of the municipal council did not like that the pillars of construction should be pushed onto the public sidewalk.
There was never any change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the city's call Josep Battlo asked (and got satisfaction) for permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and on the third a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey house is shared by a staircase through which one accesses to an independent roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were canceled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and replaced by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the living rooms and the high society can communicate comfortably or else limit the private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with the reconstruction of Gaudi has received besides new facades a non-traditional toteura and two more floors.
Gaudi’s play with the light is also impressive, with blue and white glazed tiles decorated with the inner courtyard and with the light wells.
The two-color game gives maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was enough simply to bet on the principle that white reflects more than dark which on the contrary absorbs the rays of the sun.
The Casa Battlo house that was inscribed in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund can be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and most splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous designer.
They continued the tours as they found it to be a lucrative undertaking and they expanded the scope of the tours to the common areas and attic including the roof terraces.
The entrance ticket to the monument is really cheap and costs 16.50 euros; students, retirees, groups and holders of tourist cards have 20 percent discount.
The sum is still above the entrance price to Gaudi’s other buildings in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic turrets, you must quickly find a comrade among the inhabitants of the building and visit the house completely.
