Devices to track people are increasingly in demand by parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear for their child causes more and more people to think about monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars can just as well be used to trace the movement of people and help in some cases as for example that of little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as big as a matchbox but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka moved many people and they began to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
“We are trying to tell everyone that this is not spying but just another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy,” says Petr Pilin of MAcro Weil, one of the providers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I admit there may be instances of misuse of such devices, like putting it in the bag of someone who isn't aware of it, but I haven't met such cases yet."
“The majority of people are customers who actually buy the product for safety reasons,” Pilin adds.
According to him, children should always know for what purpose "the box" is used and how to use it in an emergency.
The child psychologist, Dana Bockova, draws attention that if the child does not want to carry something of this type on him, he will get rid of it.
"And even the little ones can show great creativity when it comes to deliberately getting rid of something when they don't want to be under control."
“Mobile phones, which can be cut like these tracking devices, have already led parents to long expectations,” says Bockova.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in case of aggression is highly questionable.
“If it is a prepared abduction, the author will do everything so that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate it.”
“Currently, it’s the phone.”
"As soon as the tracking equipment develops, they (criminals) will also look for them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign."
“In such cases, criminals will always be ahead of the police,” the psychologist says.
She admits, however, that such devices can help in an unprepared assault by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an assault.
"The device can be set up in such a way that it is on regular transmission after a certain period of time."
"In the event that the device is destroyed, the last position of the person concerned remains."
“The more expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who slipped and finds himself lying down without moving,” says Cech.
According to him, so-called smart phones that are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after having formatted it with special software.
The problem with current tracking systems is that they are either similar to those worn on pendants the size of a matchbox or on smaller telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of the company Macro Weil, this is why tests are currently being carried out to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the potential attacker will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Or he'll realize it after a while, which will give the police a little more time," he added.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as for tracking cars.
This is a combination of position acquisition systems using GPS (which is commonly used in self-navigation) and a function of a mobile phone that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
