Households will pay an extra 100 kronor monthly for housing.
Households will have to pay a surcharge from January not only for all types of energy but also for water and sanitation, heating supplies and in some places rents will also rise.
Starting in January, families will have to draw up to a hundred crowns a month more than they do now.
Electricity increases by 4.6 percent, gas by almost 2 percent more expensive, in some locations you will have to pay up to a tenth more for water supply and in many places central heating supplies will also be more expensive.
The increase in electricity is expected to be close to 100 kronor per year for households in apartments.
However, all suppliers have lowered electricity prices given the sensitive development of encouraging the manufacture of renewable energies, including photovoltaic batteries.
Gas increases moderately but of course at the time when people need it most to heat and therefore have the greatest consumption.
One can also count a hundred crowns more.
Although electricity and gas are increasing throughout the Czech Republic, the change in the price of central heating differs from city to city.
It is mainly the larger municipalities that are planning the price increases.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Kraloce will pay almost 50 more kronor per month for central heating from January, while families in Liberia will pay more than 1000 kronor annually.
For the inhabitants of Prague is preparing a 9 percent increase for water and sanitation in case the city increases infrastructure rents.
If the rents do not change the pragues will pay an extra 6.8 percent.
The price in Prague will still be among the lowest in comparison with the whole country.
In northern Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and sanitation are up 7.4 percent.
For example, rent prices will rise significantly in the 450,000 apartments rented from January, that is, at the end of the regulation.
For example, CPI Byty, which owns almost 2500 apartments in Usti nad Labem, has decided to increase it by up to 100 percent.
Those who disagree with the new rent increase will be brought to court by the company.
Regulated rents that people pay in nearly 300 thousand apartments could rise by 10 percent next year.
