Two L-159 aircraft are in foreign hands for the first time in Spain.
Two of the five L-159s in total, against which the Ministry of Defense exchanged Casa C-295M transport aircraft, took off on Tuesday for Seville, Spain, where the Casa-EADS aircraft manufacturer is headquartered.
This is the first time that such devices have become the property of anyone other than the Czech Army.
However, they have been abroad as part of exercises or demonstration flights.
These are the two-seater versions of the L-159T1 that were previously in service in the Czech Army and were in flight condition.
The remaining three aircraft are single-seater versions of the L-159.
These are currently stationed at Aéro Vodochody and the commercial intermediary - the firm Omnipol - took them into account last week.
According to Jan Pejsek of the Ministry of Defense’s press department, the physical departure of Vodochody’s planes is currently unknown.
“The single-seater L-159s scheduled for exchange were taken from long-stored aircraft without causing additional burdens or investments for the Ministry of Defense.”
"The L-159 T1 two-seaters have been exchanged in the state," Pejsek told Pravo.
He said the army would not run out of two seats as the ministry signed an agreement with Aero Vodochody in May 2009 worth 200 million kronor for the transformation of four unused L-159 single-seaters into two bi-seaters.
The army took delivery of the first aircraft in July, the second being scheduled for delivery later this year.
According to Pejsek EADS is committed to introducing the aircraft into the equipment of some Alliance countries.
“It is clearly stated in the contract that the one that takes the L-159 aircraft into account is EADS and that they will be used for training pilots from NATO member countries.”
"It is therefore the business of the one who takes into account how to achieve this," Pejsek said.
Hospodarske noviny announced some time ago that the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three more aircraft for 3.5 billion kroner was approved last year by the government of Mirek Topomanek.
The Department of Defense did not tender and contacted EADS directly.
Defence management argued that the exchange ensures future export of the L-159 abroad.
The Czech Army bought 72 aircraft from Aéro Vodochody and only used 24, wanting to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft will likely have legal implications.
However, the European Commission has filed a complaint against the Czech Ministry of Defence with the European Court of Justice because the aircraft should have been chosen as part of a tender at European level and under no circumstances by contacting a manufacturer directly.
The army has already taken delivery of three Casa planes, the last one is expected to arrive at Prague Kbely airport in two weeks.
An index longer than the ring finger is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men who have the index longer than the ring finger are at a lower risk of having prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
“Our findings show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple test of prostate cancer risk, especially for men before age 60,” said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, including by combining it with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health ancestors, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed with her colleagues in Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had their right hand index shorter than the ring finger.
For them as for the 19 percent of those who had the same length of fingers, we found the same probability of prostate cancer.
In the case of those who had the index longer than the ring-shaped, however, the risk fell to 33 percent, for men before age 60, the risk decrease reached 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned - formed during the prenatal period - indicates in particular different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research has shown that it is testosterone that helps the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he is aware of the study but does not seem to think that the relationship between finger length and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
