The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) has new indications regarding a nuclear program developed by Syria.
But this country refuses to take a position on this issue, let alone submit to the agency's controls.
On the night of September 5-6, 2007, at least four Israeli F-15 fighter jets attacked a mysterious cubic-shaped building on Syrian territory.
It is located on the bank of the euphrates; the largest nearby city is 30 kilometers away: it is Dair as-Sur.
Its name appears in the IAEA documents, because it refers to the reactor that Syria apparently built with the help of North Korea in parallelepiped stone, hidden in a valley marked by the absence of electric current.
According to a U.S. intelligence briefing, the CIA, dating from the end of April 2008, the current reactor, known as the neighboring locality, el-Kibar, would be well-suited to produce plutonium, which would make it possible to manufacture atomic weapons.
However, this technique has been valid since the 1950s.
The CIA showed a presentation video featuring fuzzy satellite images.
Through computer-assisted animation, it indicated the likely location of each component of the reactor before the destruction of the plant, which represents a miniature copy of the North Korean model of the Yongbyon nuclear power plant.
In addition, she presented the photos showing the building located nearby, or even the inside of it.
It seems that the reactor was about to be put into service, but it was not yet equipped with fuel rods.
Today, more than three years after the Israeli bombing, there is scarcely more information available than at the time, and even, with time, the mystery grows thicker and thicker.
Former U.S. President George W. Bush recently revealed in his memoirs that prior to the attack, the CIA was certain that Syria had built a reactor in el-Kibar, but had little clue that the country was developing an “active nuclear weapons program.”
Some intelligence agents in Europe prefer to be more cautious about this and speak only of a “presumed reactor,” even though they consider the CIA’s presentation to be “plausible.”
They lack tangible evidence, as well as the IAEA.
Asked how he ensures he is dealing with a nuclear reactor, a high-ranking U.N. diplomat gave a laconic response in the summer by saying that the IAEA had “sufficient documents to ask questions.”
The Syrians certainly hastily removed the rubble of the “unused military building” and proceeded to a methodical flattening of the terrain.
However, in June 2008, a team of IAEA experts led by former Chief Inspector Oli Heinonen discovered in el-Kibar traces of man-made uranium.
In addition, the IAEA received satellite images from commercial providers from one member state showing the moment directly following the attack; it appears that the latter are more eloquent than those presented by the CIA.
However, these photos are not available on the market because the anonymous sponsor, perhaps Israel, acquired them exclusively.
It is therefore impossible for the IAEA to establish their authenticity objectively.
Syria has always assured that it has never carried out a secret atomic program and that it has not built a reactor.
Damascus claims that the uranium found on the site comes from weapons used by Israel.
But the IAEA rejected this argument after the analysis of the particles, calling it implausible.
Since that time, Damascus has refused to discuss this, as well as satellite images.
In addition, Syria does not allow controllers to carry out a second inspection at the el-Kibar site and denies access to the wreckage of the building destroyed by the bomb.
But even Israel keeps a stubborn silence.
Confirming the official position, Ehud Olmert, then Prime Minister in office at the time of the attack, recently said: "We will never comment on this."
This is how the investigation into this case has been dragging on since June 2008 without a result and has "become more and more a serious problem of the credibility of the Agency", as recognized by a high-ranking Western diplomat serving at the IAEA headquarters in Vienna, in the end it is a serious violation of the Treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons.
The IAEA considers that in order to make progress, it is necessary to clarify the existence of the other three facilities that must have "a functional relationship" with the alleged reactor.
So far, the inspectors have not indicated what facilities they are dealing with, or what their function is or what they are suspected of containing.
According to information published by the Süddeutsche Zeitung, they are known within the IAEA respectively as Marj as-Sultan, Masyaf and Iskandariayah also by the names of neighboring cities.
The Independent Institute for Science and International Security in Washington has identified these locations and found satellite images of a complex near Masyaf that would most likely be one of the suspect objects.
It is possible that he is in a military base or directly next to it; that is exactly why Syria denies access to the three sites to IAEA inspectors.
In Vienna, it is claimed that Syrians fear that the inspection group is actually spies who would be sent on behalf of the United States by the IAEA to spy on military installations.
In fact, it is intelligence provided by U.S. secret agents that caught the attention of nuclear inspectors.
The IAEA has information, including satellite photos, indicating that vehicles have been shuttled between the three sites and the stone parallelepiped to transport substances.
A senior Western diplomat said in Vienna that at least one of the facilities could "serve for fuel production."
It would have "no indications of sensitive activities", such as uranium enrichment and reprocessing; processes that are indispensable for the production of atomic weapons.
This type of reactor certainly works thanks to the unenriched uranium.
Nevertheless, there are plausible hypotheses regarding the following fundamental questions: where should the uranium have come from and where the plutonium needed to make the bomb would later have been separated.
It is not known whether the rubble, which could hide high-value traces, was stored at all three sites.
When the hundreds of trucks loaded with dirt are gone, no one will have information about where the rubble is stored.
For the IAEA, it is unlikely that Syria had the al-Tibni salt mine, located just a few kilometers from el-Kibar on the other side of the Euphrates, examined in 1998 to see if it could be suitable for storing radioactive waste.
By recently analyzing satellite photos taken on behalf of the famous Jane's Intelligence Review magazine, former IAEA inspector Robert Kelley has established a link between them and the reactor in question.
Satellite photos show, however, that Syria undertook earthworks at the three suspected sites and moved huge containers when the IAEA began demanding access to those sites.
It may be a coincidence, but it did not help rule out suspicions.
