Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson may have difficulty getting a look at China’s underground urban brigade.
And for good reason, the critics will say.
Unlike the police, these officers are only authorized to enforce municipal orders by imposing fines or other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese media is portraying the news of a different reality.
In January 2008, inspectors in Hubei province beat an observer to death after he used his cell phone to film them dispersing a protest against a garbage dump.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing inspectors, stolen and posted online, described how to effectively defeat offenders without bloodshed.
This year in Shanghai, a watermelon colporteur was abandoned with a brain injury after a fight with five officers.
A video game imbued with violence, available as an online download, shows Chinese inspectors trained to assault street vendors.
"Chengguan has marked the government," China Daily, a national publication, lamented last year after yet another controversy over tactics.
The newspaper called for a “true complete cleansing.”
Skeptics say the approach is far from that.
