Prosecutors will not charge Senator Ensign
Justice Department prosecutors lifted criminal charges against Senator John Ensign, stemming from a case involving an assistant in a former campaign and his efforts to get lobbying work for the woman's husband, the senator's attorneys announced Wednesday.
The decision ends the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a potential Republican presidential candidate in 2012 until the scandal surrounding his case made national headlines last year and hurt his career.
Mr. Ensign’s office said he was “very happy” with the decision, the result of a one-year investigation.
The senator could still be exposed to disciplinary action taken by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Ensign’s lawyers said the Justice Department had “notified that Senator Ensign was no longer the subject of the investigation and that he did not intend to maintain any charges against him in this case.”
The Department of Justice abstained from commenting on this matter.
The announcement came as a sort of surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, who said there was significant evidence that Mr. Ensign conspired to violate a federal criminal ban on lobbying.
Interviews, emails, and other documents, first released in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, get a lucrative lobbying job to win the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator’s affair with her.
Ms. Hampton once served as a treasurer during an Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political funders to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; according to documents and interviews.
Given that Mr. Hampton had recently been an employee of Mr. Ensign, he was prohibited from lobbying his former employer or the Senate as a whole for a year by law.
Ethics experts have argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the case, appears to contradict the so-called door-to-door ban on lobbying.
Based on the evidence that has been made public, “there appears to be prima facie evidence of a conspiracy to violate and substantial violation of the revolving door law,” said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients from a government investigation.
Although the department’s judge declined to explain the reasoning that led to the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department appeared to be wary of political prosecutions after a number of high-level cashbacks by its public integrity section, including last year’s decision to drop prosecutions of former Senator Steven Te’s wrongdoing.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, the director general of citizens’ responsibility and ethics in Washington, a advocacy group that has received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don't apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign’s senior lawyer, said in an interview that he had received a phone call Monday from a Justice Department prosecutor and a follow-up the next day, telling him that the department was not looking for charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign’s team of lawyers had cooperated with prosecutors to try to persuade them that the senator, as his office reaffirmed Wednesday in a statement, had “acted in accordance with the law.”
Mr. Coggins declined to specify the legal arguments he had made to the prosecution.
"I'm not comfortable going into the details of my discussions with the Department of Justice, except to say that we think they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission decided to drop an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, arguing that the payment of $96,000 by Mr. Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The Electoral Commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a major Nevada company that has long supported the senator, is a company for which Mr. Ensign has helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that after the company welcomed Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, Mr. Ensign’s chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Mr. Hampton and told him that he was “hammering” the Interior Ministry on a disputed issue.
Mr. Ensign also attended a luncheon with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, and asked the Transportation Secretary to set up a meeting on behalf of the airline after hiring Mr. Hampton to lobby.
When news of the case surfaced last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned from his position as the fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
After maintaining a low profile for several months, Mr. Ensign stated two weeks ago that he intended to run for a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr. Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokeswoman, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hoped that the ethics committee would quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and end its investigation.
Senator Ensign is pleased to continue her hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she says.
Cheshire's call points to Twitter
Half a dozen of them were typing far into the rows of the courtroom.
They were sending out every minute reports of horrific testimonies via Twitter.
In the end, the defense said there were more than 140,000 messages about the trial of the rape case and the children tied to their beds in a house that was set on fire.
On Thursday, the widely followed trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of the murder of three members of the Cheshire family in Connecticut, is expected to lead to an official end where the judge would impose the death penalty, voted on by the jury.
But Mr. Hayes' lawyers have already filed evidence in court that outlines appeals that could occupy the courts for years.
What is provocative is that the intense reporting on the trial - as well as the widespread and widespread use by Twitter journalists - has created a "circus atmosphere", a saturation so widespread and instantaneous with incendiary details that the jury has been badly influenced by the passions of the public.
The request could prompt appeals judges to debate whether new technologies require new rules in courtrooms.
"I have experienced this in this trial; I think there is a real danger that the introduction of new technologies in the courtrooms is infringing on human rights at a fair trial," said Thomas J. Ullmann, attorney for Mr. Hayes, chief attorney.
The trial judge, Jon C. Bleue of the Superior Court of State, laconically rejected the claims in last week’s judgment, saying the media was “carefully controlled” and there was no evidence that the jury was driven by passion.
But that doesn’t seem to be the last word on the issue.
Courts of appeal have recognized for decades that media coverage of notorious cases can raise questions about the fairness of a lawsuit.
In a 1966 landmark ruling, the U.S. Supreme Court overturned the conviction of a Cleveland osteopath, Dr. Sam Sheppard, for the murder of his wife, arguing in his ruling that there was a “carnival atmosphere at trial” because of the media.
The crime is considered by some to have been the inspiration for the television show and the film "The Fugitive".
Some lawyers have stated that appeal courts seized for reviewing a half-century later Mr. Hayes’ conviction may be curious given the argument that new rules may be needed to manage the media of the courtrooms, unimaginable at the time of Dr. Sheppard’s case.
“There’s a general reason to worry about the impact of new media” in large-scale trials, said John J. Donohue III, a professor at Stanford Law School who studied the death penalty in Connecticut and wrote a report that it was arbitrarily enforced.
Professor Donohue says some appeals judges may be intrigued by the idea that limiting instant communication from courtrooms could allow for fairer trials.
The case of Twitter is just one of many described by Mr. Hayes’ lawyers, likely to be discussed for years; which delays execution.
Defense lawyers also claim, for example, that Mr. Hayes was harmed when Judge Blue refused to allow them to test the reactions of potential jurors by showing them gruesome pictures of criminal scenes during the jury selection.
Some of the jurors said they were horrified by the photos of the victims, Jennifer Hawke-Petit, 48, and her daughters, Hayley, 17, and Michaela, 11.
Defense lawyers say they will also challenge the constitutionality of the death penalty and that they will argue that the judge unfairly expelled one of the jurors, who had been critical of prosecutors, and that he improperly put pressure on a verdict by making the unusual decision to get the jury to deliberate in a weekend.
The jurors were not kidnapped.
But their arguments about the effect of the intense media coverage of the trial could be the biggest source of interest.
They noted in a dispute against the verdict, filed last month, that the case dominated the media scene in Connecticut and that it was being discussed during the election campaign by candidates for governor and the U.S. Senate.
They maintained that the computer media were constantly igniting the flames of the emotion of the case.
“The daily jolt of tweets from the media, cameras and journalists in front of the courthouse,” the lawyers wrote, “looked like nothing that had been seen before here, in New Haven, and perhaps even nationally.”
Their focus on Twitter coverage is controversial.
In interviews, some reporters said the claim, that the snapshots were more incendiary than the slower releases, was a luddist view that would impoverish the Court’s policy governing media coverage of future trials.
But some lawyers said the courts of appeal were often drawn to the arguments that social and technological changes required adaptation by the courts.
Mr. Hayes’ lawyers insist on this claim.
In their case, they refer to the 1966 Supreme Court ruling that overturned Dr. Sheppard’s conviction because of the trial’s media coverage, and they clarified that they would invoke the need for new rules for the new media.
"This case," they wrote, "represents that of Sheppard v. Maxwell of the 21st century."
Can civility bring the divides closer together?
After a campaign marked by invective and negativity, a minimum of civility erupted in Washington this week.
Is this a warning sign of genuine bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before the rapid return to partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders has produced no breakthrough on the major issues that need to be addressed during the "lazy duck" session.
But obviously, there was at least a polite discussion about the differences of the two sides as well as acknowledging their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the committee on the president’s deficit was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created mutual respect that transcends the ideological divide; but which, however, still divides the members.
This is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
The two sides are now in a period of mutual trial and test for signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
That’s why Tuesday’s meeting and subsequent participants’ comments revealed a minimum of demands or charges.
The philosophical differences between Obama and Republicans are too big and too deep to suggest a rapid change in the climate that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxation, spending, health care or fees, both parties stay miles away.
Yet the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
“There’s no doubt that things have changed on the tone,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official, now alongside the Center for Ethical and Public Policy.
“It’s inevitable after the election.
The elections arouse partisan passions and then fade.
That's good."
On certain issues, including those on the agenda of the “lazy duck” session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of that.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all of it, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise on the extension of unemployment benefits is possible, if only because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favor of tax cuts for the rich, while denying unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, more optimism is surrounding a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on the "lazy duck", with the ratification of the "New START" pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that fruitful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the "blade duck" session will not necessarily lead to a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
“Once the things that need to be done are done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations,” he said.
Wehner also expressed widespread skepticism that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
“I consider most of what is happening between now and 2012 as a pre-show or a shadow-boxing versus the main event of 2012,” he said.
The reasons for this are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters present at the tea that contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know they must try to live up to their promises to cut public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the first reactions to the recommendations of the deficit committee that include reforming the tax code and increasing certain taxes, pushing back the retirement age and cutting spending.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have chosen one of the toughest jobs in Washington and have, they say, imposed the deficit issue on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they have struggled to reach that number.
The greatest resistance persists among the elected members of the group; this suggests that there are few reasons or willingness to compromise on fiscal issues, at least today.
Galston plans two phases in the fighting between the White House and Congressional Republicans.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, as Republicans challenge Obama in terms of budget, taxes and health care, followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of the change?
public opinion.
It is widely proven that, despite the spirit behind the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to a stalemate, as in 1995, then both parties will closely observe the public’s reaction.
The one who will be judged in loss will have to change course and find compromises.
But that would still be an optimistic view.
The partisan spirit and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and Congressional Republicans than there was then between President Bill Clinton and Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a simple prelude to a more consistent election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
Disclosed U.S. documents describe Moscow as a haven of corruption
The control of the city is in the hands of a “Kleptocracy” and passes to the Kremlin some of the bribes and protection money it collects, the U.S. Embassy in Russia said in a note in February.
The police and the Federal Security Service are carrying out huge rackets that help explain the high cost of living in Moscow, he said.
They collect money not only from legitimate businesses but also from organized criminal groups.
Every layer of bureaucracy – what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the “vertical of power” – takes its share as money moves up the ladder.
The memo, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was posted Wednesday by WikiLeaks on its website.
The note is based on sources whose names have been purged.
It was written while Yuri Lukhkov was still mayor of Moscow; and he is largely held responsible for corruption.
He was fired in October by President Dmitry Medvedev but there has since been little trace of cleansing.
Luzhkov and his wife, Elena Batourina, who owns a leading construction company, have always denied accusations of corruption over the years; and he has won several libel trials on these accusations.
In September, he told a Russian TV channel when asked about a documentary suggesting he was corrupt: “It’s crazy, it’s thrown away, it’s anything.”
The Russians believe, by an overwhelming majority, that their society is corrupt; according to the polls.
But it is unusual to find the information stated in an embassy briefing; and it is unusual to conceive that it would be for diplomats from a foreign country to do so.
The direct link between the Moscow city government and crime has led some people to call it “dysfunctional” and claim that the government functioned more as a kleptocracy than a government.
“Criminal elements enjoy a ‘krysha’ (a term used in the criminal/mafia world that literally means ‘roof’ or protection) that passes through the police, the Federal Security Service (FSB), the Ministry of the Interior (MVD) and the prosecutor’s office, as well as through the entire bureaucracy of the Moscow city government.
"Analysts identify a three-tiered structure in the criminal world of Moscow."
"Luzhkov is at the top."
“The FSB, the MVD and the militias are at the second level.”
"Finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level."
“This is an inefficient system in which criminal groups fill a gap in certain areas where the city does not provide certain services.”
The report states that the FSB is embracing the money of the largest companies and that the police are targeting the small ones.
One source, he said, “explained that Moscow business owners understood that it was better to get protection from the MVD and FSB (rather than organized crime groups) because, not only do they have more weapons, more means and more power than criminal groups but they are also protected by law.”
“That’s why the demand for protection by criminal gangs is no longer that high.”
The note notes that although the collection of money is extensive, the protection itself can be uneven; even those who pay are sometimes subject to arrest.
Those who do not pay quickly see their business close under one pretext or another.
Medvedev has mentioned the fight against corruption several times but has admitted that little progress has been made.
The embassy note conveys reports of men bringing suitcases, probably filled with money, to the Kremlin.
“In its fight against corruption, Medvedev depends on bureaucrats,” said Georgi Satarov, director of Moscow’s think tank Indem.
“But it’s part of that bureaucracy.”
“It’s not part of a political class because it doesn’t exist in Russia.”
Without politics, without opposition, without separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
According to the Indem, the costs of corruption are estimated to be more than $300 billion per year across Russia.
The country was ranked 154th in a recent survey on the global perception of corruption by the non-governmental organization Transparency International (countries are ranked at least the most corrupt).
The release of the U.S. Embassy note, which was made only yesterday, late in the evening, Moscow time, will move with certainty the discontents within the Russian government; although Lukhkov may be blamed, to some extent, for Moscow’s failures, this could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to show that it is solving the problem.
Interviewed on CNN by Larry King, Putin hypothesized that WikiLeaks documents could be fabricated and reacted angryly to the comments that U.S. diplomats had leaked calling him Batman and bringing Medvedev closer to Robin.
“The problem is that this is our interaction, which is an important factor in domestic policy in this country,” he said.
“But to be honest with you, we didn’t suspect that it would be done with such arrogance, such pressure and, you know, as opposed to ethics.”
Khmer Rouge veterans forced to face the past
In a poorly lit classroom with poor quality decrepit concrete walls, the headmaster of Anlong Veng High School talked about the man who built it, the last Khmer Rouge leader, Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves your mok."
“He was a good leader; and he cared about his people,” said 42-year-old Sreng Kor Ma.
Known as "the butcher" for his brutality, when he was at the head of the Khmer Rouge, this commander remains popular in this isolated stronghold of former Khmer Rouge in northwest Cambodia where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure; and where thousands of former Khmer Rouge soldiers still live today.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, long-standing loyalty is finally called into question in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local truth and reconciliation forum allowed the victims to publicly confront the people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed a high school textbook that, for the first time, teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to the children of its former soldiers.
And in July, a Cambodian court, jointly run with the United Nations, handed down its first sentence concerning a former Khmer Rouge member, sentencing, to 35 years in prison, the former head of Tuol Sleng’s infamous torture center, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as “Duch.”
Faced with this evolution of the situation, anxiety has increased among the veterans of the Khmer Rouge of Anlong Veng; complicating reconciliation efforts and their willingness to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
“There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge but they are powerless to do anything,” said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Centre, an independent body that conducts research on the regime.
“For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious but the regime became a symbol of evil.”
"The situation creates divisions within families."
During the reign of the Khmer Rouge in Cambodia from 1975 to 1979, about 1.7 million people were executed or died of starvation, disease or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew Pol Pot’s U.S. government in 1979, the rest of the regime and its army fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last of the movements surrendered in December 1998.
While Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary were leading the guerrilla warfare from their base located in the western mountains of Cambodia and in the jungle, Ta Mok was preparing a sequel to Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace deal led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began defecting to the government, culminating in the capitulations of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok, who had stood up, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the mountains near Dangrek.
He died in a prison in Phnom Penh in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without their benefactors, most Khmer Rouge veterans have fallen into black poverty, common to rural Cambodia; and many remain nostalgic for the movement.
Although a few elite Khmer Rouge officers retained their local leadership positions in exchange for laying down their weapons, they were low-ranking, unqualified farmers.
“These people received very little follow-up after the capitulation,” said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which organizes public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
“They are imbued with the agrarian utopian ideology of the regime.”
“They were raised in a setting where doing business is a foreign concept.”
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling in 1998 as a poor rice farmer.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"Ta Mok feeds everyone."
But now life is hard because we have to provide for our own needs.”
The ongoing Khmer Rouge court has also caused some trouble here.
The court is expected, early next year, to begin the trial of Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The court's mandate is to try senior officials and those responsible for the crimes, but it did not say whether it was pursuing beyond these four cases.
More would be needed to calm fears in Anlong Veng.
The latest media speculation has turned to 64-year-old Im Chaem, a former district chief in Banteay Meanchey province under the Khmer Rouge in the 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodia Documentation Centre that she had overseen the construction of the Trapeang Thma dam, a project where thousands of forced laborers were reportedly killed.
Recently, on a scorching evening, Im Chaem was returning from work to the field near his wooden house on stilts, on a dirt road outside Anlong Veng.
As the sun cast long shadows on the dry grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss his past within the Khmer Rouge.
If the court summoned her, she said, she would refuse to go.
“Cambodia is at peace and stable,” she said.
“If there are more prosecutions, there will be war.”
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, also warned repeatedly that instability would occur if the court sued several suspects; although experts and historians dispute this.
“Cambodia has to dig a hole and bury the past,” he said.
But facing the past is all Cambodia needs to do to move forward, says Youk Chhang of the documentation center.
“The reconciliation in Khmer terms is to reconnect the broken pieces,” he said.
“We need to put these pieces together so we can understand.”
The center produced the first government-approved manual on the Khmer Rouge, "A History of Democratic Kampuchea, consisting of 75 pages."
He distributed it in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the Ministry of Education's history textbooks, designed for high schools, which contained less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, the youth of Anlong Veng know only a few details about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city’s ties to the regime.
Touch Valeak, a 19-year-old high school student in Anlong Veng, said the new textbook helped students understand an important part of their story.
But his parents reacted with skepticism when he came home with the book to study.
“My family rejects many parts of the manual and the court,” he says.
“They are suspicious because they don’t know exactly how many people the court will prosecute.”
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, said Sok Leang.
But public forums, the manual and the courtroom are starting to make an impact, he said.
Yet the Khmer Rouge retains a powerful appeal here.
In the heights of the Dangrek Mountains, a path, overgrown with weeds and dotted with plastic bags, leads up to a rectangle of black soot, covered with a rusty sheet metal roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, a 31-year-old roadside cell phone saleswoman, said she didn’t know much about the man who was cremated there.
"But he has a great spirit; and many people go there to pray," she said.
It was Nuom Sothea’s birthday and later that day she planned to walk to Pol Pot’s last resting place where she would leave a bouquet of ripe bananas in hopes of bringing luck.
Belarus agrees to give up its stockpile of military-grade uranium
The government of Belarus announced on Wednesday that it would abandon its stockpile of highly enriched uranium, a key component for nuclear weapons; this decision is part of a surprise victory of President Obama’s campaign to secure nuclear materials worldwide.
