This paved the way for an agreement on Wednesday to eliminate the rest of the matter by about 500 pounds, according to one official who raised the condition of anonymity because of the sensitivity of the issue.
The deal appears to be one of the most important outcomes of the 47-nation Nuclear Security Summit, held at Obama’s initiative; where Belarus was excluded.
Apparently, it was profitable to procure an invitation to the former Soviet Republic following the summit in 2012.
“I’m really fascinated by the fact that they want a seat at the 2012 Nuclear Security Summit.”
“It proves to me that this process works,” said Ken Luongo, president of the Partnership for Global Security, a nuclear security advocacy group.
Clinton called the deal "a very significant, important step" by Belarus.
Obama pledged in Prague in April 2009 to secure all vulnerable nuclear materials around the world in the next four years.
Since then, the U.S. government has helped six countries get rid of all their highly enriched uranium.
