Finally, towards the end of October, Merkel again expresses a clear position, calling for the reform of the Union treaties to make it possible to rescue a country and at the same time force private lenders to bear a part of the cost.
This position was interpreted as anti-European because it precipitated the Irish crisis and the rest.
But his proposal, although somewhat sweetened, has been approved and, in the following months, we should be witnessing the Union's reform process that will make these measures possible from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not think it will cross.
And it tells us all that, even if we must now take measures with which we may not agree too much, from then on the old functioning of the euro would have ended.
2013 will signify the birth of a new monetary zone, in which countries that violate the rules will be severely punished, they may be forced to declare themselves in cessation of payments and, in that case, the private sector will also bear a portion of the costs.
Germany warns us that we must follow a strict growth path with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
An alternative based on debt and construction, with huge gaps in the balance of payments, like the one that presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, will simply not be tolerated.
The bet is clear.
And it would be wrong not to hear it.
It’s not just about bringing the public deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What we are asked to do is much harder.
And what he absolutely must not do in these circumstances is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will bring us greater peace of mind.
And let's take the opportunity we've been given, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also heard it in this form and his double statement (the reforms promised after last Saturday’s meeting with big companies and yesterday’s announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite Merkel’s criticisms, we have paved the way for the thesis to be put in order at home.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and they don’t seem to move it.
And among the possibilities that we are considering, we cannot exclude the possibility of abandoning a monetary area that is too full of countries that are not serious.
And in that case, Germany will always be able to tell us that she warned us.
Sport and Law Fraud
The tricks similar to that of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but not the will to escape a sanction.
In principle, the expulsion by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the match against Ajax in the Champions League on November 23 has caused a lot of ink on the anti-sports character of such behavior and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As we know, a few minutes before finishing the game (which their team was already clearly winning), both players deliberately lost time when they made mistakes in determining the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and since Real Madrid will eventually be the leader of his group, the two players will complete the regulatory sanction during the next match of the dam against Auxerre and will be able to move without cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA discipline committee sanctioned with two games the coach of the team, José Mourinho and different economic sums to the players involved.
Provoking a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, if not quite common in the football world.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, rules not written, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that emerged in the case is due to the fact that this had as protagonist a team of the entity of Real Madrid (who in his hymn shows nobility and honor and who on past occasions has sentenced to a fine to his players for similar acts) and to the dramatization orchestrated, it seems, by Mourinho, who added one more episode of his history to his technician.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of behavior is not expressly prohibited by the regulation and contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether with these actions one commits a fraud of the law; because, in fact, they are actions that are respectful with the sporting regulations, but seem to evade its meaning.
The question is to examine the type of harm they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the assets that includes the sporting spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions has not been endangered, that is, there has been no violent play.
Another of these assets that is alluded to with the correct game is to prevent the team of offending players from unfairly profiting from the opposing team, which is also not the case.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of Real Madrid players is that it does not accommodate what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, as its violation of the rules was not carried out in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but their action precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty of the referee.
They waited and willingly accepted the sanction.
Another question is the type of benefit that offenders obtain from the intentional faults examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that one does not put one at a disadvantage to the rival and one does not get an advantage in the same game either, because obviously the result of the action assumes the fact of leaving their own team with fewer players.
And this is not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club could not count on these players.
Obviously the advantage is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the team could be eliminated suddenly and apart from that, with this action the players complete a penalty match and move on to the second round of cards, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first round.
So, climbing the ladder is not so clear as to be an advantage.
Ultimately, these actions are not contrary to the sporting spirit, which still includes the making of strategic decisions that promote the maximum profit of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not act to avoid the application of the penalty (this would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law), otherwise they chose instead the moment in which they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without thwarting the penalty or running away from it.
Even though the boundary between genius and law fraud is widespread, on this occasion I think we've had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises because of two factors: because there have been two self-evictions and because of the way of transmitting the director to provoke them.
The harm caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
