Avengers and spies in due diligence
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it turns out to be an apparent scandal, a scandal that only appears as a scandal before the hypocrisy that governs the relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other, it heralds profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that each file made up of a secret service (of any nation) is composed exclusively of press cuts.
The “extraordinary” American revelations about Berlusconi’s sexual habits only report what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those owned by Berlusconi), and Gaddafi’s sinisterly caricatural profile has long been for cabaret artists to sketch material.
The rule that secret files should only be composed of news already known is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore devoted to esoteric publications, you will see that each book repeats exactly what was already written in previous books (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix).
And this is not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unpublished research (nor does he know where to look for news about the nonexistent), but because those who devote themselves to the occult believe only in what they already know, and that reconfirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
Same goes for the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or narrow-minded) the head of the secret service (otherwise he might be, whatever I know, a liberator), who holds only what he recognizes to be true.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. Embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as Newsweek published the week before.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what any educated person already knows, namely that the embassies, at least since the end of World War II, and since the heads of state can call or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small representation exercises, have become centers of espionage.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only through hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
Second, the idea that any hacker can capture the secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal does not put both the victims and the “brothers” in crisis.
But let’s get back to the deep nature of what happened.
In Orwell’s day, all power could be conceived as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had been completely proven since, being able to control every move through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway taken and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it is now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker – elected as the citizen’s avenger – can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that can no longer keep its own secrets?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that knowing everything about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret, because it belongs to the public domain; but revealing, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton’s secrets were empty secrets means taking away all.
WikiLeaks did nothing wrong to Sarkozy or Merkel, but made it too big for Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this injury inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer be able to put any confidential information online - that would be publishing it on a poster glued to the corner.
But it is just as obvious that with current technologies, it is in vain to hope to be able to maintain confidential reports over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a head of state flew around and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved relationships be maintained in the future?
I know well that, for the moment, my prediction is science fiction and is therefore romantic, but I am obliged to imagine government agents who move discreetly in diligence to uncontrollable routes, carrying only messages learned by heart or, at most, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shackle.
The information will be kept as a single copy in locked drawers: basically, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that the technology is now advancing in crab, that is to say backwards.
A century after wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet restored a telegraph over wires (telephones).
The (analog) videotapes had allowed the film researchers to explore a film step by step, going back and forth and discovering all the secrets of editing, while now the (digital) CDs only allow to jump from chapter to chapter, that is, by macro-portions.
With the high-speed trains, we go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the trips it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not unusual for politics and communications technology to return to horse-drawn cars.
One last remark.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was going on in the secret of the embassies.
Now, it is the embassies that are asking the press for confidential information.
Climate: How France hacks its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to look at the fulfilment of the promises of fast-start and early-start financing by developed countries.
And the big French hacks are revealed.
In the Copenhagen agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged 7.2 billion euros over three years and France 1.26 billion euros (or 420 million per year).
At the opening of the COP16, the EU took the big game out to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: report detailing the action of its member states, press conference, big side event, distribution of brochures...
Transparency is appreciable and valued: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
The EU has announced that it has released €2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on track to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look at it in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must be, according to the Copenhagen agreement, "new and additional", in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being at the expense of Public Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States whose France blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission has considered 2009 as a reference year: international financing is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years for fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or in terms of the level of official development assistance.
On the other hand, France considers the financing of "all new projects" of 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to spending in previous years or at the overall level of Public Development Assistance.
In concrete terms, the total amount of France’s support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to meet its commitment to “new and additional” financing...
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses their own calculation method.
Some, such as France, consider that 1€ lent is equivalent to 1€ given.
Of course, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the mitigation of emissions that rely on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present one euro that will be recovered as equivalent to one euro that is given... At most, it should be counted under its commitments only the cost of the loan for the lending country (i.e. the equivalent interest rate).
But France has no choice but to make such a reasoning: it “respects” its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in others) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts 1 € to fulfill its commitment, France puts only 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice trick of pass!
In short, in its fast start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of the action over time and on the other hand on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only €36.1 million, it can make it appear that it is spending €420 million "new and additional" in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other member states continue to give if it suffices to lend?) and in the negotiations since developing countries are not completely fooled...
The chapter on early financing is only a small, relatively short-term issue compared to all climate discussions.
But there could be one more grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its way of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and equity with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could advance discussions on the issues of long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently discussed): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or the method of accounting for loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
Hope rests on the new Minister of the Environment, Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the discussions.
Warning of pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in a day, according to a study published on Wednesday by the association Generations Futures (formerly the Movement for the Rights and Respect of Future Generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have a significant statistical value in view of the small number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem being treated", bought between July and September the foods usually consumed in four meals and a snack in a day by a child of about ten years, in the supermarkets of the Oise and Paris.
These standard meals, including the official recommendations – five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water a day – as well as sweets, were reviewed by laboratories looking for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The plate’s record is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens, and five substances classified as certain carcinogens, as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (EPs), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Centre.
“Although, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, it is clear from our survey that the reality of consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic contaminants and/or PE is of concern,” the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three proven to be certain carcinogens as well as nearly twenty residues that may disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, planned as a snack by the study, has traces of six chemicals, one of which is banned in France.
The same goes for Kenyan green beans, included in the lunch, on which the study detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, chopped steak, canned tuna, and even bread wand and chewing gum were stuffed with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, salmon steak was the richest with 34 chemical residues detected and even the examination of the plastic plate used to heat the meal in the microwave was not exempt.
The ultimate risk to the consumer of this "cocktail of contaminants" is "probably underestimated," according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecology-The Greens (EE-LV), for its part, proposed "in the face of the urgency of the situation" to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides, in order to stop "the increase of civilizational diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
